frameDefinitions: In this frame a Profiled_item is higher that its Standard_item on a scale with respect to some Attribute.
A New filler occupies a Role or serves a Function after the Old filler ceases to occupy the position.
These words relate to the relative ordering of two events or times.
In this frame a Speaker asks an Addressee for something, or to carry out some action.
Two or more distinct entities, which may be concrete or abstract objects or types, are characterized as being similar to each other.
An Agent displays a Characteristic of a Standard in his or her own way of behaving.
frameExamples: Notices for the Shield Theater's production of Macbeth <t>surpassed</t> all previous reviews .
<t>After</t> she arrived , she laid out her papers on the desk.

A mulberry is very <t>similar</t> in shape
to a loganberry
I guessed he was trying to <t>imitate</t> the movements of a skier
listRoleDefinitions: The role <fen>Standard_item</fen> denotes the entities that are exceeded by the <fen>Item</fen> with regard to the <fen>Attribute</fen>.
The <fen>Profiled_item</fen> is the entity that is located closest to the end of the scale evoked by some <fen>Attribute</fen>.
The <fen>Attribute</fen> is a property that evokes a scale along which the <fen>Item</fen> is located closer to one extreme in  comparison to the <fen>Standard_item</fen>.
The <fen>Standard_attribute</fen> is used when the standard is a specific value on  a scale.
The <fen>Profiled_attribute</fen> is a particular value on a scale which is being compared to an <fen>Attribute</fen> or <fen>Standard_item</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Item</fen> is higher on the scale than the <fen>Standard</fen>.
The new filler of the <fen>Role</fen> that was previously occupied by the <fen>Old</fen> filler.
The category that the <fen>New</fen> and <fen>Old</fen> entities fit into as a result of the <fen>Function</fen> they serve.
The (generally desirable) state of affairs that the <fen>New</fen> and <fen>Old</fen> entities are involved in bringing about.
The entity that occupied the <fen>Role</fen> or served the <fen>Function</fen> before the <fen>New</fen> filler.
The time at which the <fen>New</fen> takes up the <fen>Role</fen> previously occupied by the <fen>Old</fen>.

The <fen>Focal_occasion</fen> is the event which is  being located in time with respect to some other event: The <fen>Focal_occasion</fen> is profiled, in contrast to the <fen>Landmark_occasion</fen>, which is backgrounded.
The <fen>Landmark_occasion</fen> is the event  with respect to which the <fen>Focal_occasion</fen> is located.
The <fen>Focal_participant</fen> is the participant in the <fen>Focal_occasion</fen> which is profiled as being in a relation of relative time to the <fen>Landmark_occasion</fen>.
The <fen>Speaker</fen>, as in other communication frames, is generally an External Argument.
In this frame the <fen>Addressee</fen> can either occur as an NP Object (usually with a following complement clause) or as a PP Complement of verbs or nouns.
The <fen>Message</fen> is the content of the request that can be expressed as a quote, in a finite or non-finite clausal Complement, an NP Object or PP Complement.

The <fen>Medium</fen> is the physical entity or channel used to transmit the <fen>Message</fen>. The <fen>Medium</fen> is frequently expressed as a PP Complement headed by <ment>on</ment> or <ment>in</ment>.
The interval during which the <fen>Speaker</fen> makes the request.
This role marks constituents that express the set of objects or types whose similarity is at issue.

When there is an asymmetry, <fen>Entity_1</fen> is the entity characterized by its similarity to <fen>Entity_2</fen>, whose characteristics are assumed to be known.  <fen>Entity_1</fen> is often an external argument.

When the <fen>Entities</fen> are expressed separately, <fen>Entity_2</fen> is the one whose characteristics are assumed to be known; it serves as a basis for establishing characteristics of <fen>Entity_1</fen>.
This role marks constituents which express a property in respect to which the similarity of the entities is assessed.
A fact about <fen>Entity_1</fen> or the <fen>Entities</fen> that reveals how <fen>Entity_1</fen> is the same or different from other entities.  (Note the contrast with 'as to'.)
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the similarity occurs or exists.
The Place is the general area in which similarity occurs or exists
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person that borrows a <fen>Characteristic</fen> behavior from a <fen>Standard</fen>.
The <fen>Characteristic</fen> is a behavior or property that the <fen>Standard</fen> possesses and which the <fen>Agent</fen> adopts in his or her own behavior.
The <fen>Standard</fen> is the entity that exhibits a certain <fen>Characteristic</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> models their own behavior on.
The time at which the imitation occurs.
The location where the <fen>Agent</fen> imitates some entity which acts as a <fen>Standard</fen>.

Hours of eating and drinking followed <fex>the wedding ceremony</fex>.
